04946nam a22006855i 9780823281909DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232819097 a10.1515/97808232819092doi  a(DE-B1597)554977  a(OCoLC)1061098343  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0671202bisacsh04a261.8223/eng1 aDrexler-Dreis, Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDecolonial Love :bSalvation in Colonial Modernity /cJoseph Drexler-Dreis. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. What Is Decolonial Love? -- tPart I. Christian Theology in the Networks of Colonial Modernity -- tChapter 1. Colonial Modernity as a Historical Context -- tChapter 2. The Entanglement of Christian Theology and the Coloniality of Power: The Possibilities of a Response -- tChapter 3. Decolonial Openings in Theologies of Liberation -- tPart II. Decolonial Love -- tChapter 4. Frantz Fanon’s Decolonial Love: A New Humanism in Historical Struggle -- tChapter 5. James Baldwin’s Decolonial Love: Uncovering the Revelation of the Beat -- tPart III. Theological Refl ection as a Decolonial Option -- tChapter 6. The Theological Pedagogy of Frantz Fanon and James Baldwin -- tChapter 7. Decolonizing Salvation -- tConclusion. Sharpening Decolonial Options in the Present Moment -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing together theologies of liberation and decolonial thought, Decolonial Love interrogates colonial frameworks that shape Christian thought and legitimize structures of oppression and violence within Western modernity. In response to the historical situation of colonial modernity, the book offers a decolonial mode of theological reflection and names a historical instance of salvation that stands in conflict with Western modernity. Seeking a new starting point for theological reflection and praxis, Joseph Drexler-Dreis turns to the work of Frantz Fanon and James Baldwin. Rejecting a politics of inclusion into the modern world-system, Fanon and Baldwin engage reality from commitments that Drexler-Dreis describes as orientations of decolonial love. These orientations expose the idolatry of Western modernity, situate the human person in relation to a reality that exceeds modern/colonial significations, and catalyze and authenticate historical movement in conflict with the modern world-system. The orientations of decolonial love in the work of Fanon and Baldwin—whose work is often perceived as violent from the perspective of Western modernity—inform theological commitments and reflection, and particularly the theological image of salvation.Decolonial Love offers to theologians a foothold within the modern/colonial context from which to commit to the sacred and, from a historical encounter with the divine mystery, face up to and take responsibility for the legacies of colonial domination and violence within a struggle to transform reality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLiberation theology. 0aLovexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aPostcolonial theology. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Liberation.2bisacsh  aFranz Fanon.  aJames Baldwin.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311072273440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823281909zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823281909423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823281909/original  a978-3-11-072273-4  Fordham Universit